  "opinion": "As a plumber with a background in practical problem-solving but limited formal education beyond upper secondary, I've seen how science can be both a tool and a barrier in everyday life. The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers—it's about who gets to shape the tools we use to fix the world. I've noticed that in my work, women often take on roles that require precision and patience, skills that are undervalued in traditional science narratives. The gap isn't a simple 'more women in labs' issue; it's about how society frames what counts as 'scientific' work. For instance, when I fix a leaky pipe, I'm not doing 'science' in the academic sense, but I'm applying the same principles of observation and iterative testing. Yet, when it comes to high-stakes scientific fields like biotech or quantum physics, the narrative often ignores the contributions of women who've been quietly shaping these areas. We should address this gap not by pushing more women into labs, but by redefining what 'science' means in practical, community-oriented contexts. My kids, who are all around 10-14 years old, ask me about the 'science' in everyday things like how water flows or why paint dries. That's the real work—I want to show them that science isn't just for textbooks but for fixing things, understanding nature, and building a better world for everyone. The solution isn't about changing the system but about changing how we talk about science so that it feels relevant and accessible to all, especially those who might not have had the chance to pursue formal degrees. It's time to stop asking 'why are there fewer women in science?' and start asking 'how can science serve more people?'",
